common features with high implementation variability based on application needs should be handled outside the framework through Nablarch Business, which suggests this distinction is intentional but not fully documented in s3.\n\nThe knowledge file does capture the critical problems that arise from prohibiting database access, so that part checks out. Now I'm verifying whether there are any unsupported claims in s1 about Nablarch's RDBMS independence policy.\n\nLooking at the table mappings, the Java type conversions appear accurate—strings, numeric types, and date/time formats all align with what the source describes. The date field uses an 8-digit string format in yyyyMMdd, and I'm checking whether the datetime mapping is complete.\n\nThe framework intentionally doesn't support automatic updates to common metadata fields like creation/modification timestamps and user information. The reasoning is that updating these fields on frequently-used operations would increase table update costs and degrade performance.\n\nFor business logic access to framework-defined tables, there are two main issues: you can't join framework tables with application-specific tables, and bulk operations like batch registration APIs or data loaders become unavailable during record creation or updates, reducing efficiency. When columns are added during version upgrades...\n\nContinuing with version compatibility...\n\nThe document has three main sections covering RDBMS independence, common field updates, and framework table access. I'm verifying the section structure matches the knowledge file with sequential IDs, and checking that the hints are comprehensive across all sections.\n\nLooking at the hints for section 1, I see Java class types like String, BigDecimal, and Timestamp are all covered, along with primitive types and date/time format patterns. The Oracle-specific type names like VARCHAR2 and DATE aren't included in the hints, but that's correct since the V4 validation focuses on PascalCase class names, annotations, and exception names rather than database type keywords.\n\nFor section 2, the hints capture the common audit fields like creation and update timestamps, creator/updater info, and deletion flags, though \"削除日\" from the source is missing—a minor gap. Section 3 appears comprehensive with its coverage of table access patterns, business logic, versioning, and data operations.\n\nLooking back at the V4 validation criteria, \"削除日\" wouldn't qualify as a required hint anyway since it doesn't match the specified categories of PascalCase class names, annotations, property names from tables, or exception names. So this isn't actually a V4 compliance issue. The knowledge file seems accurate overall, but I should double-check the source details for section 2 to be thorough. アプリケーションでは、慣例的、あるいは機能的な要求により「最終更新日時」、「最終更新者」、「作成日時」、「作成者」、「削除フラグ」、「削除日」といったカラムをテーブル間で共通的に付与することがある。フレームワークはテーブル更新時に共通項目の更新機能を基本的にサポートしないが、知識ファイルの「等」という表現で削除関連のカラムも含まれていると考えられる。ただし、ソースには共通項目を付与する場合、これらを画一的に更新するポリシーを設定することが一般的だと述べられているのに対し、知識ファイルではこの実装パターンについて明示的に言及されていない点が若干の隔たりとして存在する。\n\nまた、フレームワークが提供する機能は業務ロジックから頻繁に使用され、アプリケーション要求による影響が発生しづらいロジックに限定されるという詳細も知識ファイルには含まれていない。\n\nこれは設計原理として重要だが、主要なポリシー（アクセス許可）と理由（アクセス禁止による問題）、提供される保証は捉えられているので、細かい省略に過ぎない。\n\nテーブル定義のセクションについても確認すると、ソースは「2つの目的」に言及しているが、知識ファイルではこれが明示されていない。実際のところ、ソース自体がこの2つの目的を明確に列挙していないようだ。\n\n知識ファイルは本質的に問題ないと判断できるので、クリーンとしてマークしよう。","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":2,"cache_creation_input_tokens":20229,"cache_read_input_tokens":29873,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":20229,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":8},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"dfa4bd2b-c9d7-439a-b41b-cb6cd81df708","uuid":"92428f51-3e99-478a-85b3-de6a901902b1"}
